Here are the platforms ViSP is currently known to run on, with links to
platforms-specific notes, including any known bugs or incompatibilities:

<ul>
  <li><a href="platform-notes.html#Linux">Linux</a>
  <li><a href="platform-notes.html#SunOS">SunOS</a>
  <li><a href="platform-notes.html#Solaris">Solaris</a>
  <li><a href="platform-notes.html#Irix">Irix</a>
  <li><a href="platform-notes.html#Windows">Windows 95, 98, Me, NT, 2000, and XP</a>
</ul>

<hr>
<center><b><a name="Linux">Linux</a></b></center>

There are no known problems with using ViSP on production versions of
Linux/x86. We do our Unix development mainly on Linux/x86 with the Gnu g++
2.96, 3.2.x, 3.3.x or 3.4.x compiler.

<hr>
<center><b><a name="SunOS">SunOS</a></b></center>

There are no known problems with using ViSP on SunOS. We compile ViSP
only with the Gnu g++ 2.7.2 compiler.

<hr>
<center><b><a name="Solaris">Solaris</a></b></center>

There are no known problems with using ViSP on Solaris. We compile ViSP
either with the CC 5.1 compiler or with the Gnu g++ 2.95.3, 2.96, 3.0.4, 3.1, 3.2 or
3.3 compiler.

<hr>
<center><b><a name="Irix">Irix</a></b></center>

There are no known problems with using ViSP on Irix. We compile ViSP either with Gnu g++ 2.95.2, or with CC 7.3.3.3m.

<hr>
<center><b><a name="Windows">Windows 95/98/Me/NT/2000/XP</a></b></center>

There are no known problems with using ViSP on Windows 95, 98, NT, 2000 and
Me.

Under Windows platforms, ViSP can be either compiled using <a href=http://www.cygwin.com>Cygwin</a> or with Microsoft Visual C++.

Cygwin is a UNIX environment, developed by Red Hat, for Windows. After
installing Cygwin follow the <a href=installation.html>installation steps</a>
for Unix platforms.

If you want to compile ViSP using Microsoft Visual C++, use the Visual Studio project (.dsp) file provided in the windows directory (only in ViSP Professional Edition).


  */	